        "number": 5,
        "title": "The tithe — holy already, before the vow",
        "range": "27:30-34",
        "excerpt": "Thus all the tithe of the land, of the seed of the land or of the fruit of the tree, is the Lord's; it is holy to the Lord.",
        "body": "The chapter's final section pivots from voluntary consecration to mandatory obligation — a pivot that is exegetically significant. The tithe is not introduced here as a new law (it was established in Genesis 14:20, Numbers 18:21-24, and Deuteronomy 14:22-29) but as the counterpart to the vow system the chapter has just regulated. After twenty-nine verses of machinery for transferring common property into the holy sphere, the tithe reminds the reader that some property is already in that sphere — not by human decision but by divine declaration.\n\nThe agricultural tithe of verse 30 covers the seed of the land and the fruit of the tree — the two primary outputs of an agrarian economy. Both are 'the Lord's' and 'holy to the Lord' in the simple present tense. The Israelite does not make them holy by tithing; he acknowledges their already-holy status by delivering them. The redemption provision of verse 31 (pay valuation plus one-fifth) applies when an Israelite wishes to keep the physical produce and pay its cash equivalent instead — perhaps when transportation to the sanctuary is impractical. The surcharge, as throughout the chapter, ensures that the substitution costs more than the obligation.\n\nThe livestock tithe (vv. 32-33) is governed by a different mechanism — not priestly assessment but the random counting rod. Every tenth animal that passes under the shepherd's rod is holy, regardless of quality. The vow-maker cannot inspect the herd first and arrange the counting to favor the sanctuary with inferior animals; the selection is randomized precisely to prevent that manipulation. And any attempted substitution (v. 33) triggers the same penalty as the clean-animal pledge of verse 10 — both animals become holy. The closing words of the tithe section — 'it shall not be redeemed' (v. 33) — echo the cherem language of verse 28, placing the tithe alongside the most irrevocable category of the chapter. The tithe belongs to the Lord; it cannot be bought back.\n\nThe colophon of verse 34 closes not only the chapter but the entire book of Leviticus: 'These are the commandments which the Lord commanded Moses for the sons of Israel at Mount Sinai.' The Sinai anchor is the book's final word. All of Leviticus — from the burnt offering of chapter 1 to the tithe regulation of chapter 27 — flows from the same divine speech at the same mountain. The book that began with the Lord calling from the tabernacle (1:1) ends with the Lord's address at Sinai — two modes of the same divine initiative, bracketing the entire sacrificial and holiness legislation in the character and command of the God who speaks.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Maaser* (tithe) — literally a tenth; the same root as eser (ten). *Shevet* (rod, 27:32) — the shepherd's counting staff, the same word as the tribal rod and the royal scepter; here the instrument of random sacred selection. *Mitsvah* (commandments, 27:34) — the legislative term that closes both chapter 26 (v.46) and chapter 27, asserting that Leviticus is not priestly tradition but covenantal command."
